/staff/beth_rhoden.jpg" alt="" class="float-left rounded">
				<h2>Beth Rhoden <br><small>Executive Director</small></h2>
				<p>I never really wanted to be a nurse.  I wanted to fly airplanes, but my dad said that was a “job for boys”.  On the heels of this bad news, my best friend convinced me to go to nursing school during our senior year of high school.  I could either graduate early, or enroll in our local community college and stay eligible to run on the track team one last year.  So… nursing it was!</p>
				<p>Turns out, it was my calling – although it took me a few years and a few career changes to figure it out.  Within a short time of graduation, I decided that I didn’t want to get stuck in my west Michigan farm town, so I ran away to visit my sister in Petersburg, Alaska – and immediately got stuck in a fishing village!  Ultimately it was a happy stuck, but that took me awhile to realize too!  I worked in the small 7 bed hospital in Petersburg for a couple of years, then started raising babies.  During my kids younger years, I worked as a travel agent – something that I could do part time and take my son with me while I worked.  I then worked for a chiropractor and realized how much I missed medicine, so became an EMT and ran on the volunteer ambulance crew.  The majority of my calls were 1 am bar fights, but every once in awhile I got to help rescue a life, bring a new life into the world, save a life, or hold a hand at the end of life.  During that time, I started my 10 year career with the Department of Fish and Game.  First as an Admin Assistant for the Division of Habitat, where I learned much about Environmental Impact Statements, the eco-system and about Alaska’s gifts, and the challenges she faced.  From there I transferred into the Division of Sport Fish, then Commercial Fisheries, and finally into the Wildlife Division, where I pulled bear teeth sealed furs and issued hunting/trapping permits.  I had never considered myself much of a “tough girl”, but that job proved me to be just that.  Tough.</p>
				<p>When my marital situation changed, that toughness really kicked in.  I decided that it was time to get back to my “grown up” job of nursing.  I packed my car and hopped on the ferry and sset out for my next adventure.  Back to nursing school – to start over again!</p>
				<p>My nursing career has given me many opportunities – I ran a PCA and respite agency for a few years, and was the Assistant Head Nurse in a Family Practice Clinic for 10 years.  Being a single parent, I spent many years working two jobs – clinic by day, Pioneer Home charge nurse by night.  That renewed my love of the senior population and I jumped at the opportunity when I was offered a position as a Regional Nursing Director for a senior living company based out of Las Vegas.  After a couple of years, I realized how much I missed Alaska, so took a position as a Nurse Liaison for St. Elias Specialty Hospital here in Anchorage.  During my time at St. Elias, I started a healthcare networking group called SPOTLIGHT on Healthcare where I met many wonderful people from all aspects of  healthcare from the Mat Su valley, down to the Central Peninsula.  When I learned that my son was giving me the ultimate gift of a grandbaby, I loaded up and headed BACK down to Las Vegas.  I accepted a position as Memory Care Director, where I was fortunate enough to care for 40-56 seniors with Alzheimers and other cognitive impairments.  Then as Director of Nursing for a 105 bed Assisted Living Facility.  But the biggest during that time of course, was that I was honored to be present for the birth of my first grandchild, Ruthie Grace, and shortly thereafter, grandson Elliott Cole came along.</p>
				<p>I have recently returned once again, home to Alaska.  I am THRILLED to be a part of the Aspen Creek Senior Living family and honored to be in a position where I can help residents transition into this phase of life, and help families adjust to what can be a difficult time.  I am a firm believer that aging is a privilege not given to everyone – and we should honor every minute.</p>
				<p>Aspen Creek Senior Living is a very special place.  From the minute you walk through the doors and into our community, I hope you feel a warm sense of home.  Alaska’s seniors and their families deserve the very best care, and you have my word that OUR family will take great care of YOURS.</p>
